Reference Label Generation Rules for the Korean Script

Overview

This document specifies a reference set of Label Generation Rules (LGR) for the Korean script for the second level. The starting point for the development of this LGR can be found in the related Root Zone LGR [RZ-LGR-Kore]. The format of this file follows [RFC 7940].

For details and additional background on the script, see “Proposal for a Korean Script Root Zone LGR” [Proposal-Korean], including the appendices [Proposal-Korean-Appendices]. The term “Korean script” is usually synonymous with “Hangul”. However, in the context of the Korean LGR, “Korean script” refers to the union of Hangul Syllables and Han characters used in writing Korean (Hanja).

This document is a Review Draft and not final. Any version numbers shown are those of a possible future release. However, the draft may undergo significant revisions before any publication, or may be withdrawn.

Repertoire

According to [Proposal-Korean], the repertoire of 15,930 code points is based on [MSR-5], which is a subset of [Unicode 11.0] and is defined in [RZ-LGR-Kore]. The repertoire includes 11,172 Hangul syllables and 4,758 Hanja characters for a total of 15,930 code points (11,172 + 4,758). For more details, see Section 5, “Repertoire” in [Proposal-Korean].

For the second level, in addition to the code points and sequences defined in [RZ-LGR-Kore], the repertoire has been augmented with the ASCII digits, U+0030 to U+0039; the ASCII lowercase letters, U+0061 to U+007A; and U+002D HYPHEN-MINUS, for a total of 15,967 repertoire elements. Unlike many other non-Latin Second Level Reference LGRs, the Korean LGR includes the basic ASCII Latin set (a to z) because it is common practice in Korean text to mix Korean and ASCII. Therefore it does not create confusability or additional security risks in the context of a Second Level LGR for the Korean language. It is also supported by current IDNA practice, see [700], for example.

Other code points outside the Korean script repertoire that are listed in this file are targets for out-of-repertoire variants and are identified by a reflexive (identity) variant of type “out-of-repertoire-var”. They do not form part of the repertoire.

Repertoire Listing: Each code point or range is tagged with the script or scripts with which the code point is used, and one or more references documenting sufficient justification for inclusion in the repertoire, see “References” below.

For more details, see Section 5 “Repertoire” in [Proposal-Korean].

Variants

There are no variants defined between Hangul syllables. However, the LGR defines 37 variant sets among Hanja, and 7 variant sets containing at least one Hangul syllable. All additional variants between in-repertoire Hanja required by integration with the Chinese LGR [CLGR] are also listed.

Altogether, this LGR lists 289 variant sets, which can be classified as follows:

  • 283 variant sets consist of variants between two or more Hanja characters that are part of this LGR repertoire. One of these variant sets also includes a Hangul syllable.
  • 4 variant sets consist of variants between one or more in-repertoire Hanja character and a Hangul syllable. This includes one variant set already included in the previous group.
  • 3 variant sets consist of variants between one out-of-repertoire Hanja character and a Hangul syllable. One variant set also includes one in-repertoire Hanja character.

Because one variant set is classified in both group 1 and 2, the total of variant sets is 283+4+3-1 = 289.

Additional Variants: In addition to the variants listed in this LGR, any integration into a zone including Chinese and Japanese LGRs will result in many additional variants to out-of-repertoire code points as result of variants defined in other LGRs, including the effects of transitivity. However, the list of in-repertoire variants in this LGR is exhaustive.

Variant Mapping Types

All non-reflexive variant mappings defined are of type “blocked” and all reflexive ones of type “out-of-repertoire-var”. For more details, see Section 6 “Variants” in [Proposal-Korean].

This LGR does not define allocatable variants.

Source References for Variants

The following source references are used for variant entries in this LGR:

  • [201] - Korean-specific variants among Hanja (Table 1-1 in Appendix F)
  • [202] - Korean-specific variants between Hangul and in-repertoire Hanja (Table 1-2 in Appendix F)
  • [203] - Korean-specific variants between Hanja and out-of-repertoire Hanja (Table 1-3 in Appendix F)
  • [204] - In-repertoire Hanja variants originating from [300] (Table 2-1 in Appendix F)
  • [300] - in-repertoire variants originating from the Chinese LGR [CLGR]

Character Classes

This LGR defines the following named character classes:

  • hanja — Hanja code points
  • hangul — Hangul code points

Whole Label Evaluation (WLE) rules and Context Rules

Default Whole Label Evaluation Rules and Actions

The LGR includes the rules and actions to implement the following restrictions mandated by the IDNA protocol. They are marked with ⍟.

  • Hyphen Restrictions — restrictions on the allowable placement of hyphens (no leading/ending hyphen and no hyphen in positions 3 and 4). These restrictions are described in Section 4.2.3.1 of RFC 5891 [120]. They are implemented here as context rule on U+002D (-) HYPHEN-MINUS.

  • Leading Combining Marks — restrictions on the allowable placement of combining marks (no leading combining mark). This rule is described in Section 4.2.3.2 of RFC 5891 [120].

Korean-specific Rules

This LGR does not define rules specific to the Korean script.

Actions

Default Actions

This LGR includes the default actions for LGRs as well as the action needed to invalidate labels with misplaced combining marks. They are marked with ⍟. For a description see [RFC 7940].

Korean-specific Actions

A label may consist of Hangul syllables or Hanja characters only; no mixes are allowed. See also Section 7, “Whole Label Evaluation Rules (WLE)” in [Proposal-Korean].

  • no-hangul-hanja-mixed-label — a WLE rule triggering a Korean-specific action invalidating any mixed labels

Methodology and Contributors

This reference LGR for the Korean script for the second level has been developed by Michel Suignard and Asmus Freytag, based on the Root Zone LGR for the Korean script and information contained or referenced therein, see [RZ-LGR-Kore]. Suitable extensions for the second level have been applied according to the [Guidelines] and with community input. The original proposal for a Root Zone LGR for the Korean script, that this reference LGR is based on, was developed by the Korean Generation Panel. For more information on methodology and contributors to the underlying Root Zone LGR, see Sections 4 and 8 in [Proposal-Korean], as well as [RZ-LGR-Overview].

References

References [0] to [3] refer to the Unicode Standard versions in which corresponding code points were initially encoded. For example, a reference value of [3] means a character was first encoded in Unicode Version 3.0.

References [101] and up indicate that the code point is included in one of the following source references: [101] ‘kIRG_KSource’ values starting by K0 in the Unihan database and [102] ‘kIICore’ values including the letter ‘K’(indicating source) in the Unihan database.

Entries in the table may have multiple source reference values.
